==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic: cognate with Old Saxon [[slahan]] (Dutch [[slaan]]), Old High German [[slahan]] (German [[schlagen]]), Old Norse [[sla|slá]] (Swedish [[slå]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌻𐌰𐌷𐌰𐌽]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /slæ:an/

===Verb===
'''slēan''' (class VI strong)
# to [[beat]] or [[strike]]
# to [[kill]], especially violently; to [[slaughter]]
#:''slogan fram eastsæ oð westsæ ond him nænig wiðstod.''  They slaughtered from the east coast to the west and none withstood them.  (Bede)
# to [[slaughter]] an animal for food

===Noun===
# slean or slane, Hiberno-English word (from the Irish sleán) -- a spade for cutting peat. The slean or slane consists of an iron head and a long wooden shaft. The head has a flat blade, generally with a wing on one side, so that sods can be cut on two sides and detached with a single twist of the implement. There are basically two kinds: the breast sleán and the foot sleán, with two correspondingly different methods of cutting from the turf bank.


